            <p>During this period I spent time investigating how we subjectivly interpret sound and the driving question of "what is music?". This initiative started by prototyping 'musical' distortion units in a program called MaxMSP, which I used to track and manipulate fundemental frequencies. Surround sound recording techniques also caught my attention; I wanted to know "how do we capture the sound of physical enviroments and reproduce such richness in our living rooms?". To find out, I experimented with a number of techniques leveraging <i> head related transfer functions</i>: <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binaural_recording">binaural heads</a>, <a href="https://lossenderosstudio.com/article.php?subject=17">hamasaki squares and optimised cardioid triangles</a> to be precise. All different models mapping the terrain in various ways. </p> 
            <p>Eventually my research cumulated in the question of "why do we tend to prefer the aesthetic qualities of certain sounds over others?" namely I focused on the age old debate of analogue vs digital (specifically tubes vs transistors) and eventually surfaced the inherent laws of vibration; precicely what pythogoras meant when he proclaimed "the octave never repeats". In this case it turned out that tubes produce second (rather than third) order harmonic distortion, leading to intermodulation frequencies (sum and difference) that give rise to the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_tuning">pythagorean mucical scale</a> at smaller and smaller fractal dimensions! </p>
            
            <div class="flex justify-center grid-cols-2 bg-primary-200 rounded-lg p-4 mb-4">
